1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Three replicas, new image, zero downtime, that's a deployment.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,400
A deployment manages a set of paths.

3
00:00:10,400 --> 00:00:12,760
You describe the desired state.

4
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:17,080
The controller continuously reconciles actual to desired.

5
00:00:17,080 --> 00:00:19,720
Under the hood, it wraps a replica set.

6
00:00:19,720 --> 00:00:22,560
You don't touch replica sets directly.

7
00:00:22,560 --> 00:00:26,480
Change the image tag, and a new replica set spins up.

8
00:00:26,480 --> 00:00:30,640
The old one scales down gradually, never all at once.

9
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:34,960
The old replica set is kept, that's your rollback target.

10
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:38,000
Four operations you need to know.

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,240
Scale replicas up or down instantly.

12
00:00:41,240 --> 00:00:46,000
Roll back to a previous revision with Cubectl Rollout Undo.

13
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,240
Pause a rollout to batch multiple changes, then resume.

14
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:54,000
Check progress with Cubectl Rollout status.

15
00:00:54,280 --> 00:00:57,480
A how you run stateless apps in production.

16
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:02,560
Set the replica count, set the image, let Kubernetes handle the rest.

17
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:05,640
Run the docs, Kubernetes deployments.

